@NASAInternships help prepare students to become part of the future workforce for the nation and at @NASA. 💫⁣
⁣
Throughout the year, thousands of students intern at NASA - contributing to the missions of human space flight, space science and Earth research. 🌎⁣
⁣
For students seeking a NASA internship, here is a message from current and former #NASAinterns: go for it, apply! 🚀⁣
⁣
To all former and current interns: thank you for contributing to NASA missions and inspiring the #Artemis Generation in all that you do. Happy #NationalInternDay! ✨

⁣

⁣
✅ @NASAAstronauts’ Jonny Kim⁣
✅ #NASASTEM leader Elaine Ho ⁣
✅ #NASAinterns⁣
⁣
Visit NASA STEM at nasa.gov/stem to see resources available for students and apply for @NASAInternships at intern.nasa.gov. 💫

Santa Perez Cortes is a senior studying geological and earth science at the University of Puerto Rico-Mayaguez. ✨⁣
⁣
While her experience at @NASA was remote, she was able to contribute to real-world research to NASA missions at @NASAGoddard in Greenbelt, Maryland. Santa shares with students how a NASA internship provides the real-world experience. 🌎⁣
⁣
Visit intern.nasa.gov to get your intern journey started today. #NASAinterns​ #NASASTEM​ #WomensHistoryMonth

Sarah Adewumi is a senior at @umesnews, studying business administration.✨ 

Sarah aspires to work with NASA for its innovation and commitment to pioneerism in space exploration, scientific discovery and aeronautics research. Her projects have included working in communications and STEM Engagement, where she has implemented a can-do attitude while taking on all tasks with a positive energy.🚀
 
In fall 2020, Sarah participated in her third internship with @NASAAmes. She is now onto her fourth internship at @NASA_Langley for spring 2021! Listen to what she has to say to students interested in a NASA internship. 💫#NASAinterns #NASASTEM

Today is #IntroduceAGirlToEngineeringDay and this is what an engineer looks like 😎:⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
✅ #NASASTEM leader⁣⁣
✅ NASA Perseverance Mars Rover flight director⁣⁣
✅ @NASA intern⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
...and much more!⁣⁣
 ⁣⁣
@NASA recognizes the contributions of our female engineers and the importance of introducing engineering to female students at an early age. Visit NASA’s Office of STEM Engagement at nasa.gov/stem and @NASAJPL_Edu to learn about resources available for students. You could be the next NASA intern! Apply today at intern.nasa.gov to get an out-of-this world experience! 🌎

As we conclude #NationalMentoringMonth, we leave you meeting one of our #WomenAtNASA. ⁣
⁣
At a young age, Naseem Rangwala pursued her dreams by embarking a career in astronomical research. She has done just that and much more. ⁣
⁣
Naseem is an @sofiatelescope (Stratospheric Observatory for Infrared Astronomy) project scienctist and astrophycist at @NASAAmes. She is also one of our many @NASA mentors! ⁣
⁣
Naseem's personal goal is to inspire the next generation of scientists and engineers by integrating them through astronomical research with NASA's SOFIA mission. Listen to Naseem's message to students: "apply for a NASA internship. You're guaranteed to be inspired." ✨⁣
⁣
Visit intern.nasa.gov to get your NASA internship journey started today. #NASAInterns #NASASTEM

"Mentoring is important to me as I have been a benefactor of it's work." - Debrina Harrell, Information Technology Specialist at @NASA Headquarters.⁣⁣ 
⁣⁣
That work for Debrina Harrell began when she was an electrical engineering undergraduate student at @southernu_br. The value of mentorship she experienced then, impacted her 19 year career trajectory.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Today, Debrina has mentored students at NASA for over 8 years. One of her goals as a mentor is to help students realize the value they can bring to NASA. Listen to her message to students and apply to a NASA internship today at intern.nasa.gov. ⁣
⁣
#NationalMentoringMonth #NASAinterns #NASASTEM

node.text:
✨ If you’re seeking a mentorship experience, read this testimonial by our intern, Katalina Bustamante! ⬇️⁣
⁣
“If you had told me 4 years ago that I would be working with @NASA, I would have laughed. Up until this year, dreams were just dreams. ⁣
⁣
However, today marks my last day of my virtual NASA Internship at @NASAKennedy Space Center (KSC). These past 10 weeks have been so amazing and they flew by too fast! ⁣
⁣
Working in the Exploration Research and Technology directorate at KSC has been so eye opening and rewarding. I hope to continue InSitu Resource Utilization Research in the future and continue to learn all that I can. ⁣
⁣
Although I am so sad to say goodbye (for now), I am so grateful for the mentoring from all the people I met this summer. Thank you to my mentor, the GaLORE team, and the Applied Chemistry Lab for teaching me so much, mentoring me, and offering me your kindness.”⁣
⁣
Katalina is a rising senior studying chemical engineering at the @ccnycitycollege. ⁣
⁣
📚 This weekend, visit #NASASTEM at nasa.gov/stem to see student opportunities for you as you go #BackToSchool. If you’re seeking a NASA internship experience, visit us at intern.nasa.gov. ⁣
⁣
#WomenInSTEM #NASAinterns #WomenAtNASA

node.text:
📚 Celebrate #BackToSchool with @NASA! Let us know: what are your goals for this school year? 🙌⁣
⁣
Sarah Estep interned at our @NASAArmstrong Flight Research Center in California as a systems engineer working on a project called Mars Glider Swarm. 🔴⁣
⁣
The project’s goal was to send a swarm of gliders to Mars that will cover large areas of the atmosphere for data sensing and collection. Sarah helped make a release mechanism, called a gondola, that will hold up to six gliders and let them go remotely. 💻⁣
⁣
With the help of Sarah’s work, Mars Glider Swarm will contribute to future Artemis missions by helping us better understand Mars’ atmosphere for safe human spaceflight. Sarah was a senior at @MoreheadState University majoring in Space Systems Engineering.⁣
⁣
Visit #NASASTEM at nasa.gov/stem for the many student & educator opportunities available to you. 😍

node.text:
“I want to lead projects that my kids, my kids kids and their kids will benefit from. I think I get this ambition from my mother, who is a first-generation immigrant who fled to the United States from Iran during the Iranian revolution,” David Pantera said. 

As an intern at @nasaames, Pantera works on the Small Business Innovation Research and Small Business Technology Transfer (SBIR/SBTT) team. This team funds the research, development, and demonstration of innovative technologies that fulfill @nasa needs and have significant potential for successful commercialization.

🥤When Pantera was asked to hypothetically select any role in NASA’s plans to send humans to the Moon or Mars, Pantera responded he wanted to be a bartender at the ‘NASA Space Cantina.’

“Through that role, I'd love to hear the stories, passions, backgrounds and motivations of the innovators, businesspeople, scientists, researchers, drifters, adventurers and others who pass through the station,” Pantera said.

📌 What would your dream role be in the @nasaartemis mission?

@NASAInternships help prepare students to become part of the future workforce for the nation and at @NASA. 💫⁣
⁣
Throughout the year, thousands of students intern at NASA - contributing to the missions of human space flight, space science and Earth research. 🌎⁣
⁣
For students seeking a NASA internship, here is a message from current and former #NASAinterns: go for it, apply! 🚀⁣
⁣
To all former and current interns: thank you for contributing to NASA missions and inspiring the #Artemis Generation in all that you do. Happy #NationalInternDay! ✨

🔭 Save the date! National Intern Day will take place on July 29. Events include: U.S Federal Agency Interns asking questions to @nasaastronauts on the @iss, Reddit AMA, a @nasa Science Live episode, and interns attending the orbital flight launch at @nasakennedy! 

📌 Tune in to our events and find more information with times and virtual locations on the guide tab within our profile!

“It's so funny because I remember, in middle school, I would always tell my friends and family how I wanted to work for @nasa, and they would laugh about it because I don't think anyone back home has ever done something big like that. Having them see me working here -- it just kind of opened their eyes, like, ‘Wow, it's possible,’ you know,” Leah Teodoro said. 

🌊 Leah Teodoro grew up on the remote island of Saipan in the middle of the Pacific Ocean and her dream of one day working for NASA always seemed a bit far-fetched to those around her. Teodoro studied geophysics at the @uhmanoanews and was an intern at @nasajpl — making her dreams a reality.

“I do feel more confident in being a minority and a woman in STEM. I feel more driven to be successful and to inspire people from back home to go and pursue what they want to do. Don't let the confinements of your environment stop you from what you want to do,” Teodoro said.

Do you have a similar experience? Does anyone from your hometown inspire you? Comment down below!

🧭 After a high school physics teacher peaked his interest in space technologies and exploration, Ved Vakharia became hooked on the idea of performing science somewhere else than Earth. He earned a degree in mechanical engineering and is on his way to earning a PhD in materials science and engineering at @ucsandiego.

👨🏽‍🏫 Vakharia’s physics teacher inspired him to explore. What mentors or teachers have inspired you?

Vakharia has interned at @nasa_langley and currently interns at @nasaglenn. He works on characterizing the feasibility of 3D printed, metal-infused polymers as structural materials. He also uses engineering simulation software to model different welding methods (ultrasonic, induction, resistance) of thermoplastic joints in order to understand the methods' effects on degree crystallinity, residual stress development, and joint strength.

🌡 Vakharia hopes the spacecraft that takes humans to the Moon or to Mars, @nasaartemis, will have a component made from ablation-resistant ceramic materials that can withstand the high temperatures and oxidizing environments that he helped develop.

Joshua Ott works with 347 Mobility and Robotic Systems at @nasajpl in support of the DARPA Subterranean (SubT) Challenge. The SubT Challenge is focused on developing innovative technologies that would augment operations underground. 

🪐 Ott explores new approaches to rapidly map, navigate, search, and exploit complex underground environments, including human-made tunnel systems, urban underground, and natural cave networks. Ott studies aeronautics & astronautics at @stanford.

“You don’t need to know everything. You don’t necessarily need to only apply for programs that you have previous experience in. It’s just as important to show passion and interest in areas that you have no prior knowledge about! Don’t be afraid to take a chance,” Arianna Dwomoh said.

📓Arianna Dwomoh is interning at @nasagoddard and studies physics and math as a sophomore at @dukeuniversity. Dwomoh works on JWST Commissioning & Keck 3-micron Dust Emission Studies. It is a combination of science focused and non-science focused research. She is also currently investigating spectral variation of PAHs within the planetary nebula NGC 7027 by fitting the features with a Gaussian and measuring the equivalent widths.

📌Have questions about @nasainternships? Check out our website or FAQ highlights!

“Honestly, it's somewhat unreal to be working on something that's so important and so new. It's not monotonous work. It's not like you're just punching numbers —

🪐 Everything that I'm working on has the potential to be implemented in some sense for the very first time on another planet. That's something that makes me excited to go to work every day,” Brandon Ethridge said.

📓As a first generation college student, Ethridge attended North Carolina A&T and graduated with a degree in mechanical engineering with a concentration in aerospace. 

Ethridge went on to accept a full-time position with the team at @nasajplcareers as a Systems Engineer after his internship at @nasajpl! 

What’s your dream career at @nasa? Visit intern.nasa.gov for more information on @nasainternships!

node.text:
Calling all potential interns! If you missed out on our fall deadline, don’t fret. Start getting ready now by reading words of wisdom from our current summer interns!

Students often want to hear from current #NASAinterns so we brought them to you. We had our summer interns weigh in on the things they wish they knew before becoming a @nasa intern. Swipe through this post to read these current intern items to have a better understanding of our internship program.

1. You don't have to be in STEM to appreciate STEM.
2. NASA people are amazing and inclusive.
3. Be kind to yourself.
4. There is space for curiosity.
5. It is never too late.
6. There is a team supporting you along the way.
7. Keep exploring! 

Are you interested in an internship with NASA? Learn more about @nasainternships and the Artemis Generation at intern.nasa.gov! Check back mid-fall for spring internship applications and follow us for further updates. What advice resonated with you the most?

Max Rudolph interned at @nasajpl and worked on the Mars rover. Max’s role was to find bugs in the software that directs the precise movements of the camera that serve as the 👀 of the rover and ensure that the swivels of the rover’s ‘head’ performs efficiently. Max is a student at @georgiatech studying electrical engineering.

“I've mostly been testing the cameras and the movements of the remote-sensing mast. 📷 So we move the remote-sensing mast around, use the cameras on the front of the mast to take pictures and see whether it can do what it's designed to do. We get instructions from the subsystem engineers, the people who designed and built different parts of the mast [such as the cameras and science instruments]. We try out the movements and commands they designed to see if they actually work when the whole system is together,” Max Rudolph said.
